412 WUTHERING HEIGHTS.

We buried him, to the scandal of the whole
neighbourhood, as he had wished. Earnshaw,
and I, the sexton and six men to carry the

ﬂin, comprehended the Whole attendance.

The six men departed when they had let it
down into the grave: we stayed to see it co-
vered. Hareton, with a streaming face, dug
green sods, and laid them over the brown
mould himself, at present itis as smooth and ver-
dant as its companion mounds—and I hope its
tenant sleeps as soundly. But the country
folks, if you asked them,\would swear on their
bible that he walks. There are those who
speak to having met him near the church, and
on the moor, and even within this house—Idle
tales, you’ll say, and so say I. Yet that old
man by the kitchen ﬁre afﬁrms he has seen two
on ’em looking out of his chamber window, on
every rainy night, since his death—and an odd
thing happened to me about a month ago.

I was going to the Grange one evening—a

dark evening threatening thunder—and, just

